  "text": "Gonadal sex reversal in XY Fgfr2 hob/hob embryos is associated with a failure to maintain high levels of the key testis determinant, SOX9, after 11.5 dpc. In contrast, the proovarian gene Wnt4 is elevated, indicating sex reversal of the supporting cell lineage. These data are consistent with observations of failure to maintain Sox9 expression in Fgf9-deficient XY gonads [CITATION_1] . In contrast, Sry expression appears to remain unaffected by disruption of FGF9/FGFR2 signalling. Recent studies involving phenotypic analysis of XY embryos lacking Fgf9 and Wnt4 suggest that the primary role of FGF9 may be to inhibit the activity of WNT/b-catenin signalling [CITATION_2] . The mechanistic basis of this at the molecular level remains unclear, but Fgfr2 hob/hob embryos may offer a useful tool for investigating such antagonistic interactions of the testis-and ovary-determining gene regulatory networks (Carre & Greenfield). However, an inhibitory role for FGF9/FGFR2 signalling may suggest that the search for targets of FGF-dependent signalling in the gonad should be extended to proteins associated with ovary development and canonical WNT signalling more generally.",
